ture have grown in response to conflicts over space ever since the United States' annexation of Mexican territory in the 1840s. Then, turning to the work of contemporary members of the Chicano intelligentsia such as Helena Maria Viramontes, Ron Arias, and Lorna Dee Cervantes, Villa demonstrates how their expressive practices re-imagine and re-create the dominant urban space as a community enabling place. In doing so, he illuminates the endless interplay in which cultural texts and practices are shaped by and act upon their social and political contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCity and town life in literature. 0aHispanic American neighborhoods in literature. 0aLocal color in literature. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aMexican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aSetting (Literature). 0aSpace and time in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292798922423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292798922/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK